  "prompt": "The prime factorization of intezer N is A x A x B x C, where A, B and C are all distinct prine intezers. How many factors does N have?",
  "response": "Let's analyze the prime factorization of the integer \\( N \\). Given that:\n\n\\[ N = A \\times A \\times B \\times C \\]\n\nwhere \\( A \\), \\( B \\), and \\( C \\) are distinct prime integers.\n\nThis means \\( N \\) can be written as:\n\n\\[ N = A^2 \\times B \\times C \\]\n\nTo find the number of factors of \\( N \\), we use the formula related to the exponents in its prime factorization. The total number of factors of a number \\( N \\), which has a prime factorization of:\n\n\\[ N = p_1^{e_1} \\times p_2^{e_2} \\times \\cdots \\times p_k^{e_k} \\]\n\nis given by:\n\n\\[ (e_1 + 1) \\times (e_2 + 1) \\times \\cdots \\times (e_k + 1) \\]\n\nFor \\( N = A^2 \\times B \\times C \\), the exponents of the prime factors are:\n\n1. \\( A \\) has an exponent of 2.\n2. \\( B \\) has an exponent of 1.\n3. \\( C \\) has an exponent of 1.\n\nTherefore, the number of factors of \\( N \\) is:\n\n\\[ (2 + 1) \\times (1 + 1) \\times (1 + 1) \\]\n\nCalculating this:\n\n\\[ 3 \\times 2 \\times 2 = 12 \\]\n\nSo, the integer \\( N \\) has 12 factors.",
